  "prompt": "How does a SSD differ from RAM? What are the advantages and disadvantages to both?",
  "response": "Let me break down the differences between SSDs (Solid State Drives) and RAM (Random Access Memory):\n\nSSDs (Storage):\nAdvantages:\n- Permanent storage (data remains after power off)\n- Large capacity (256GB-4TB typical)\n- Faster read/write speeds than traditional hard drives\n- No moving parts, more durable\n- Silent operation\n\nDisadvantages:\n- More expensive per GB than HDDs\n- Limited write cycles (gradually wear out)\n- Slower than RAM\n- Higher power consumption compared to HDDs\n\nRAM (Memory):\nAdvantages:\n- Extremely fast data access\n- Temporary, high-speed working memory\n- Allows quick processing of active applications\n- Low latency\n- Enables multitasking\n\nDisadvantages:\n- Volatile memory (loses data when power is off)\n- Much smaller capacity (4-128GB typical)\n- More expensive per GB\n- Generates more heat\n\nKey Differences:\n1. Purpose: RAM is for active processing, SSDs are for long-term storage\n2. Speed: RAM is much faster\n3. Volatility: RAM loses data, SSDs retain data\n4. Capacity: SSDs have much larger storage capabilities\n\nBoth are crucial for computer performance, serving different but complementary roles in a computer system.",
